Interpretation and limitation
-----------------------------
The --cache-type-k flag IS parsed by the canister's arg parser -- this was
verified independently by passing "--cache-type-k INVALID_XYZ" which produced
the expected exception "Unsupported cache type: INVALID_XYZ" (canister log
entry around 2026-04-20T18:13:57Z). However, when passed at run_update time
on this patched wasm build, the flag is functionally a no-op: the KV cache
has already been allocated with f16 precision at the model's first lazy
load (which happened earlier in this session via run_update without any
--cache-type-k). Subsequent run_update calls just reuse the already-allocated
KV tensors; llama.cpp does not re-allocate the cache to honor a changed
--cache-type-k on an existing context.

Evidence this is the failure mode (not a true quality-equivalence finding):
  1. Bit-identical decode across all three settings at the same seed is
     extremely unlikely if the KV quant actually differed -- q4_0 KV
     introduces enough per-layer noise to alter sampling in practice.
  2. The canister's load_model endpoint, which IS the correct entry point
     for --cache-type-k (it controls cache allocation), consistently trapped
     with "heap out of bounds" every time it was invoked during this
     session (exit code IC0502, canister log "common_init_result: fitting
     params to device memory" followed by [TRAP]: heap out of bounds).
     This reproduces whether or not --cache-type-k is passed. load_model
     is reliably broken on this patched wasm build once the context has
     been populated once; attempts to force re-init would require a full
     wasm re-install.
  3. The wall-clock differences (13.43 vs 10.94 vs 10.73 s) do not track
     KV compute cost; they track probe ordering (f16 is the first arm
     measured after fresh new_chat, incurs re-tokenization + initial
     prompt eval overhead; q8 and q4 inherit the warm context).


Actionable conclusion for Paper 1.5 Phase 2
-------------------------------------------
Task 17 result: "cache-type-k is RUNTIME-ACCESSIBLE on this wasm build
(parser accepts the flag and rejects invalid values with a clear error)
but is NOT functionally EFFECTIVE at run_update time because KV cache
allocation happens at model-load time, and load_model traps reliably on
this patched wasm once a context exists. A true f16 / q8_0 / q4_0 KV
trade-off measurement requires rebuilding the wasm with either (a) a
working load_model path that can swap KV cache type, or (b) the flag
baked in at compile time per arm with separate wasm artifacts. Punt to
next wasm iteration."

Per the task protocol: data still recorded to CSV (rows
c3-kvtype-qwen05-{f16,q8,q4}) so downstream analysis can see both the
wall-clock numbers AND this caveat. The CSV notes column flags
"prompt=hi-cat;probes=10,15,20;90s-timeout" but does NOT claim the KV
was actually quantized -- the bit-identical decode above refutes that.


